"""
MKT Original Commentary — Judges chapters 11–13
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-judges-11-13-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/judges.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json (key terms)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/judges.json (MKT text)

Key decisions in this range:
- Jephthah vow (11:30-31, 39): text is genuinely ambiguous; both sacrifice and
  consecration readings noted; v39 "knew no man" phrase favors lifelong celibacy
- pālîʾ/pelîʾî (13:18, H6383): translated "beyond understanding" / "wonderful";
  connected to peleʾ root and Isa 9:6 messianic title
- malʾak YHWH: rendered Angel of the LORD throughout; the text's own recognition
  scene (13:21-22) signals the angel = YHWH himself
- Chemosh (11:24): Jephthah uses ius gentium argument, not polytheism
- Shibboleth (12:5-6): dialectal /ʃ/ ~ /s/ distinction; not purely theological
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JUDGES = {
  "11": {
    "1": "<p><em>gibbôr ḥayil</em> (H1368 + H2428) — &ldquo;mighty warrior/man of valor&rdquo; — the same honorific used of Gideon (6:12) and Boaz (Ruth 2:1). The juxtaposition with <em>bên-ʾiššāh zônāh</em> (son of a prostitute, H802) is abrupt: the text establishes Jephthah&rsquo;s military credential before naming his social liability. <em>Gilʿādî</em> (the Gileadite) at the end of the verse completes the triple identification — Jephthah is a Gileadite warrior of prowess whose birth excludes him from the inheritance he should have had.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>naḥălāh</em> (H5159, inheritance) governs the conflict: Gilead&rsquo;s legitimate sons deny Jephthah his portion. The Hebrew phrase <em>lōʾ-tinḥal bəḇêt-ʾāḇînû</em> — &ldquo;you will not inherit in our father&rsquo;s house&rdquo; — is a formal legal exclusion. Israelite inheritance law tied <em>naḥălāh</em> to the status of the mother; a son of a slave-woman or prostitute could be excluded if the father&rsquo;s legitimate heirs objected (cf. Ishmael, Gen 21:10).</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>ʾănāšîm rêqîm</em> (H376 + H7386, empty/worthless men) — the same phrase used for Abimelech&rsquo;s retinue (9:4). The parallel is deliberate: like Abimelech, Jephthah attracts a marginal following when legitimacy is denied. <em>Tôḇ</em> as a place-name (location uncertain, perhaps in northern Transjordan) means &ldquo;good&rdquo; — an ironic settlement name for a displaced outcast. <em>wayyēṣēʾ ʾittô</em> — they raided with him — establishes his career as a mercenary warlord before his commission.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Narrative transition: <em>miyyāmîm</em> (H3117, after some time/days) — the formula marks an unspecified lapse before the Ammonite crisis. The elders&rsquo; need reverses the power dynamic established in v2; the rejected son becomes the only viable military leader.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The elders of Gilead make the journey to retrieve Jephthah — a reversal that the narrator frames as driven by necessity (<em>wayyāqumû</em>, they rose up). The verb <em>lāqaḥ</em> (H3947, to take/fetch) acknowledges they are bringing him back on his terms, not theirs.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>qāṣîn</em> (H7101, commander/ruler) — the elders&rsquo; initial offer. The term is military and functional rather than covenantal; it offers command authority without social rehabilitation. Jephthah&rsquo;s counter-negotiation in vv.8-11 upgrades this to <em>rōʾš</em> (head/chief), securing a permanent civic position alongside the military role.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jephthah&rsquo;s direct challenge (<em>lāmmāh</em>, why?) rehearses the injustice: <em>śənēʾtem</em> (you hated me, H8130) and <em>gāraštem</em> (you expelled me, H1644). Both verbs are perfects — completed acts Jephthah refuses to overlook. His return is not unconditional; he negotiates from grievance rather than gratitude.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The elders&rsquo; counter-offer expands: now <em>rōʾš</em> (H7218, head/chief) over all the inhabitants of Gilead, not merely military commander. The political elevation is the concession Jephthah required; it transforms a military commission into a permanent civil authority.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Jephthah frames the arrangement as conditional on YHWH&rsquo;s action: <em>ʾim-YHWH yittên ʾet-bənê ʿammôn</em> — the victory is divine gift, not Jephthah&rsquo;s personal achievement. This theological frame will re-appear in the vow (v30) and in the argument to the Ammonite king (vv.21-23): YHWH is the real warrior and judge.</p>",
    "10": "<p><em>YHWH yihyeh šōmēaʿ bênênû</em> — &ldquo;YHWH shall be the one hearing between us&rdquo; — covenant-witness language. <em>šōmēaʿ</em> (H8085, hearing/witnessing) frames YHWH as the enforcer of the agreement; violation becomes not merely breach of promise but sin against YHWH. The verbal covenant sealed at Mizpah (v11) is thus given divine sanction.</p>",
    "11": "<p><em>rōʾš wəqāṣîn</em> — the dual title ratifies both civic and military authority. <em>waydabbēr Yiptāḥ ʾet-kol-dəḇārāyw lipnê YHWH bammizpāh</em> — &ldquo;Jephthah spoke all his words before YHWH at Mizpah&rdquo; — the covenant terms are stated in YHWH&rsquo;s presence, constituting a formal oath before the divine witness invoked in v10.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Diplomatic protocol: Jephthah sends messengers (<em>malʾāḵîm</em>) rather than attacking immediately — unusual for judges, who typically respond with force. This extended diplomatic exchange (vv.12-28) showcases Jephthah as a legal reasoner who argues Israel&rsquo;s case from historical precedent before resorting to war.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The Ammonite claim: Israel took their land when coming from Egypt — specifically the territory from the Arnon to the Jabbok and Heshbon. Historically, this was Amorite territory (Sihon&rsquo;s kingdom) that Israel captured in Num 21, not Ammonite land; Jephthah&rsquo;s response will press exactly this distinction.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Second embassy — the repetition of messengers (<em>šûḇ</em>, again) emphasizes Jephthah&rsquo;s exhaustion of diplomatic channels before armed conflict. The legal argument in vv.15-27 is the fullest diplomatic speech in Judges.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Jephthah&rsquo;s denial is categorical: <em>lōʾ-lāqaḥ Yiśrāʾēl ʾet-ʾereṣ Môʾāḇ wəʾet ʾereṣ bənê ʿammôn</em> — &ldquo;Israel did not take the land of Moab or the land of the Ammonites.&rdquo; The legal strategy is to distinguish between Moabite/Ammonite territory (which Israel bypassed per Num 20-21) and Amorite territory (which Israel conquered from Sihon).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The wilderness itinerary recapitulates Num 20-21: Israel went through the desert from Egypt to the Red Sea and then to Kadesh — respecting the borders of Edom and Moab throughout. This is the foundational claim of the legal brief: Israel&rsquo;s route of travel did not encroach on Ammonite land.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The request to pass through (<em>naʿbərāh-nāʾ bəʾarṣeḵā</em>) was refused by the king of Edom; a parallel request to Moab was also refused — but neither Edom nor Moab went to war over Israel&rsquo;s presence. Jephthah uses the precedent to distinguish refusal to yield passage (which Israel accepted) from active military contest (which only Sihon initiated).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The wilderness detour around Edom and Moab is mapped precisely: past Edom, past Moab, arriving on the eastern side of the Arnon — always outside the Ammonite border. The geographical specificity grounds the legal argument; Jephthah knows the itinerary texts of the Pentateuch.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Sihon embassy (<em>šəlaḥ Yiśrāʾēl malʾāḵîm ʾel-Sîḥôn</em>, cf. Num 21:21-22) is identical to the earlier requests: a request for passage, not conquest. The distinction matters legally — Israel&rsquo;s intent was transit, not territorial seizure; Sihon transformed the encounter into a war by refusing and attacking.</p>",
    "20": "<p><em>wəlōʾ-hehĕʾmîn Sîḥôn</em> — &ldquo;Sihon did not trust Israel to pass through his territory.&rdquo; <em>hehĕʾmîn</em> (H539 Hiphil, to believe/trust) is the verbal root of <em>ʾĕmet</em> (faithfulness); Sihon&rsquo;s failure of trust provoked the war. This reframes the conquest as defensive rather than aggressive on Israel&rsquo;s part.</p>",
    "21": "<p><em>wayyittên YHWH ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl ʾet-Sîḥôn wəʾet-kol-ʿammô</em> — &ldquo;YHWH the God of Israel gave Sihon and all his people into the hand of Israel.&rdquo; The passive recipient of Amorite territory is YHWH&rsquo;s gift to Israel, not Israel&rsquo;s independent seizure — the legal and theological crux of the entire argument.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The territorial scope of the gift: from the Arnon to the Jabbok, from the wilderness to the Jordan. These are the same boundaries the Ammonite king claims in v13. Jephthah establishes that this was Amorite land (Sihon&rsquo;s), not Ammonite, making the Ammonite territorial claim false on its own historical terms.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The theological summation: <em>YHWH ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl hôrîš ʾet-hāʾĕmōrî</em> — &ldquo;YHWH the God of Israel dispossessed the Amorites.&rdquo; <em>hôrîš</em> (H3423 Hiphil, to dispossess/drive out) places the action entirely with YHWH; the rhetorical question follows: &ldquo;Are you to possess what YHWH our God has given us?&rdquo;</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Chemosh argument: <em>ʾăšer yôrîšeḵā Kəmôš ʾĕlōhêḵā</em> — &ldquo;whatever Chemosh your god gives you to possess.&rdquo; This is a <em>ius gentium</em> (law of nations) argument, not a concession that Chemosh is real: Jephthah uses the Ammonite theology to make a parallel legal claim. The logic is &ldquo;by your own principles, territorial possession follows divine grant.&rdquo; This does not imply Israelite polytheism.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The Balak precedent (<em>Bālāq ben-Ṣippôr</em>) adds a historical-legal argument: even the most hostile Moabite king did not go to war to recover the territory Israel possessed for 300 years. Long non-contestation equals legal acquiescence in ancient near-eastern custom.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The 300-year possession claim (<em>šəlōš meʾôt šānāh</em>) asserts prescriptive title: Israel occupied Heshbon and the Transjordanian towns for three centuries without Ammonite challenge. The span corresponds roughly to the period from the conquest to Jephthah&rsquo;s era. The rhetorical question &ldquo;why did you not recover them in that time?&rdquo; presses the laches argument.</p>",
    "27": "<p><em>YHWH haššōpēṭ</em> — &ldquo;YHWH the Judge&rdquo; — Jephthah&rsquo;s final appeal elevates the dispute to divine jurisdiction. <em>šōpēṭ</em> (H8199) is the same root as the term for Israel&rsquo;s judges; YHWH is the supreme judge over inter-national disputes. Jephthah has exhausted legal argument; he submits the outcome to divine verdict.</p>",
    "28": "<p><em>wəlōʾ šāmaʿ melek bənê ʿammôn</em> — &ldquo;the king of the Ammonites did not listen.&rdquo; The stark brevity after Jephthah&rsquo;s elaborate legal argument marks the failure of diplomacy. <em>šāmaʿ</em> (H8085, to hear/heed) is the same verb used for YHWH&rsquo;s attentiveness in v10; the Ammonite king&rsquo;s deafness contrasts with YHWH&rsquo;s role as the hearing witness.</p>",
    "29": "<p><em>rûaḥ YHWH hāyətāh ʿal-Yiptāḥ</em> — &ldquo;the Spirit of the LORD came upon Jephthah.&rdquo; The identical construction appears at Othniel (3:10), Gideon (6:34), and Samson (13:25, 14:6, 19); the Spirit&rsquo;s <em>ḥāyāh ʿal</em> (being upon someone) is the divine empowerment pattern for Israel&rsquo;s deliverers. Jephthah&rsquo;s subsequent military success is attributed to the Spirit, not his warrior skill alone.</p>",
    "30": "<p><em>wayyiddār Yiptāḥ neder laYHWH</em> — &ldquo;Jephthah vowed a vow to the LORD.&rdquo; <em>nādar neder</em> (H5087 + H5088) is a cognate-object construction that intensifies the solemnity: not simply &ldquo;he vowed&rdquo; but &ldquo;he vowed a vow&rdquo; — comparable to &ldquo;he dreamed a dream&rdquo; or &ldquo;he sinned a sin.&rdquo; The vow is conditional on military victory: <em>ʾim-nātôn tittēn</em> (if you will indeed give) uses the infinitive absolute to signal certainty of intention.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The vow&rsquo;s terms: <em>hayyôṣēʾ ʾăšer yēṣēʾ middalṯê ḇêtî</em> — &ldquo;whatever goes out from the doors of my house.&rdquo; The Hebrew has two consecutive clauses: <em>wəhāyāh laYHWH</em> (&ldquo;it shall be the LORD&rsquo;s&rdquo;) and <em>weheʿĕlîtîhû ʿōlāh</em> (&ldquo;and I will offer it as a burnt offering&rdquo;). Whether the second <em>waw</em> is conjunctive (and) or disjunctive (or) determines whether Jephthah envisions one action (consecration-then-sacrifice) or two alternatives (if an animal, burnt offering; if a person, dedicated to YHWH). The text preserves the ambiguity without resolution.</p>",
    "32": "<p><em>wayyittēn YHWH ʾôtām bəyādô</em> — &ldquo;YHWH gave them into his hand.&rdquo; The victory formula identical to the judge-cycle pattern; YHWH&rsquo;s agency is foregrounded over Jephthah&rsquo;s military action. The brief narrative of battle (v32-33) stands in contrast to the elaborate diplomatic speech; the actual war is almost incidental.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The victory geography: from Aroer to Minnith (20 cities) and Abel-keramim — a broad sweep across Transjordanian territory. <em>makkāh gədôlāh məʾōd</em> (a very great blow) is the deuteronomistic superlative indicating complete defeat. The Ammonite claim of v13 is answered by military outcome rather than legal verdict.</p>",
    "34": "<p><em>bittô yəḥîdāh lô</em> — &ldquo;she was his only child (<em>yāḥîd</em>).&rdquo; <em>yāḥîd</em> (H3173, only/unique) is the same word used for Isaac in Gen 22:2 (your only son, whom you love). The echo is likely deliberate: the father who offered his only child, the child who accepted the sacrifice. <em>tuppîm ûmāḥôlôt</em> (tambourines and dancing) mark the homecoming celebration; the daughter comes to greet the returning warrior, the very scenario the vow implied.</p>",
    "35": "<p><em>wayyiqraʿ bigādāyw</em> — &ldquo;he tore his clothes&rdquo; (mourning gesture). <em>ʿāḵôr ʿăḵartinî</em> — &ldquo;you have brought me very low&rdquo; — lit. &ldquo;you have troubled/bent me.&rdquo; <em>pāṣîtî pî ʾel-YHWH</em> — &ldquo;I have opened my mouth to the LORD&rdquo; — acknowledges the binding force of the vow; <em>lōʾ ʾûḵal lāšûḇ</em> — &ldquo;I cannot take it back.&rdquo; Jephthah treats the vow as irrevocable, which accords with Num 30:2 (a man must not break his word).</p>",
    "36": "<p>The daughter&rsquo;s response demonstrates extraordinary covenantal integrity: <em>ʿăśēh-lî kāʾăšer yāṣāʾ mippiḵā</em> — &ldquo;do to me according to what has gone out of your mouth.&rdquo; She grounds her acceptance in the premise that YHWH has avenged Jephthah against his enemies; the vow and its fulfillment are inseparable from YHWH&rsquo;s role as the one who gave the victory. Her language echoes the legal framework of the entire chapter.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The daughter&rsquo;s request: two months to wander with her companions on the mountains and weep over her <em>bəṯûlîm</em> (H1331, virginity). The word choice is significant: she mourns her virginity/youth, not her impending death. If Jephthah intended human sacrifice, weeping over barrenness is an unusual focus; the text&rsquo;s emphasis on virginity fits the consecration-to-lifelong-celibacy interpretation.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Permission granted; she goes for two months with her companions. <em>wattēleḵ hîʾ wərêʿôtêhā watteḇke ʿal-bəṯûlêhā</em> — the mourning is communal (with her companions) and specifically for her virginity, not for loss of life. The narrator&rsquo;s precision here signals what is grieved.</p>",
    "39": "<p><em>wayyaʿaś lāh ʾet-nidərô ʾăšer nāḏār</em> — &ldquo;he did to her his vow which he had vowed.&rdquo; The outcome statement is followed immediately by the clause <em>wəhîʾ lōʾ yādəʿāh ʾîš</em> — &ldquo;and she had not known a man.&rdquo; This parenthetical notation is the text&rsquo;s interpretive key: the narrator marks her permanent virginity as the defining outcome, not her death. Had she been killed, the virginity clause would be irrelevant to the narrative. The execution of the vow is described with <em>ʿāśāh</em> (he did, H6213), which for a burnt offering would normally use <em>ʿālāh</em> or <em>šāḥaṭ</em>.</p>",
    "40": "<p><em>ḥōq bəYiśrāʾēl</em> (H2706, a statute/custom in Israel) — <em>tānāh</em> (H8567, to commemorate/rehearse/lament) is an unusual verb; the daughters of Israel kept a four-day annual mourning. The word <em>tānāh</em> appears only here in the Hebrew Bible, possibly meaning &ldquo;to rehearse in memory.&rdquo; The custom memorializes specifically Jephthah&rsquo;s daughter, not Jephthah — a mark of the narrator&rsquo;s sympathy for the victim of the vow.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>Ephraim&rsquo;s complaint repeats the pattern of 8:1-3 (their grievance against Gideon): inter-tribal jealousy over military honor. <em>ṣāpônāh</em> (to the north) indicates they crossed northward toward Gilead. The threat to burn Jephthah&rsquo;s house escalates the confrontation from 8:1-3, where Gideon pacified Ephraim with diplomacy; Jephthah will not.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jephthah&rsquo;s rebuttal is terse and factual: <em>ʾîš rîḇ hāyîtî waʿammî ûḇənê ʿammôn məʾōd</em> — &ldquo;I and my people were in great conflict with the Ammonites.&rdquo; His claim that he called Ephraim and they did not come is unverified by the narrative of ch11 — but the narrator neither confirms nor denies it, leaving Jephthah&rsquo;s assertion uncontested.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>wāʾāśîmāh napšî bəḵappî</em> — &ldquo;I put my life in my own hands.&rdquo; This idiom (lit. &ldquo;placed my soul in my palm&rdquo;) expresses risking one&rsquo;s life; <em>nāpāš</em> (H5315) as the seat of life, <em>kap</em> (H3709) as the open palm. Compare 1 Sam 19:5 (Jonathan uses the same idiom for David). The phrase underlines that Jephthah acted without Ephraimite support and won anyway.</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>ʾattā pəlîṭê ʾeprayim ʾattā giləʿād</em> — &ldquo;You are fugitives of Ephraim, O Gilead.&rdquo; This tribal insult — that Gileadites were Ephraimite refugees — was the provocation for the battle. The Transjordanian Israelites were viewed by Cisjordanian tribes as marginal; Ephraim&rsquo;s slur triggers a civil war. <em>wayyakke giləʿād ʾet-ʾeprayim</em> — &ldquo;Gilead struck Ephraim&rdquo; — civil war, Israel killing Israel.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Gileadites secured the Jordan fords (<em>maʿabrôt hayyardēn</em>) — strategic chokepoints across which Ephraimite survivors had to pass. The fords are the same terrain used in Gideon&rsquo;s pursuit of Midian (7:24-25); controlling them means controlling who escapes.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>ʾĕmār-nāʾ šibbōlet</em> — &ldquo;Say now Shibboleth.&rdquo; <em>šibbōlet</em> (H7641) means either &ldquo;ear of grain&rdquo; or &ldquo;flowing stream&rdquo; — the phonological content mattered less than the dialectal distinction. Ephraimite dialect lacked the /ʃ/ phoneme, producing <em>sibbōlet</em> instead; the Gileadite ear detected the substitution. The result: 42,000 Ephraimite dead at the fords. This is the Hebrew Bible&rsquo;s most explicit account of a dialectal accent being weaponized.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jephthah&rsquo;s tenure: six years. The formulaic close (<em>wayyišpōṭ</em> + years + death + burial) reduces one of Judges&rsquo; most complex figures to a brief summary. Burial &ldquo;in one of the cities of Gilead&rdquo; — the vagueness contrasts with the precision of minor-judge burial notices in vv.8-15, perhaps a textual lacuna.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Ibzan of Bethlehem — probably Bethlehem in Zebulun (Josh 19:15) rather than the Judean Bethlehem, given the Zebulunite context. <em>šāpaṭ</em> (H8199, judged) is the only term applied; no Spirit, no military action, no divine evaluation.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Thirty sons and thirty daughters: the large family is a status indicator in the ancient world, evidence of prosperity and influence. The exogamous marriage pattern — daughters sent out, daughters brought in from outside the clan — reflects political alliance-building through kinship ties. Ibzan commanded the resources to arrange sixty such alliances.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Burial at Bethlehem — the formulaic close for the minor judge cycle. The brevity of vv.8-10 mirrors the brevity of Ibzan&rsquo;s recorded activity; these are administrative rather than narrative entries.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Elon the Zebulunite — ten-year tenure. No military action, no divine speech, no narrative. The sequence of minor judges (Ibzan, Elon, Abdon) creates a pattern of social stability between the turbulent stories of major judges; their formulaic notices mark passages of time in which Israel neither revolted nor was oppressed.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Buried at Aijalon in Zebulun — distinguished from Aijalon in Dan (Josh 19:42). The tribal identification <em>haZzəḇûlônî</em> frames the territory of his authority; burial location anchors the judge to his clan territory.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Abdon son of Hillel the Pirathonite — Pirathon is in the hill country of Ephraim (v15). Abdon&rsquo;s Ephraimite origin immediately follows the Ephraimite civil war narrative of 12:1-7, creating an ironic reversal: the tribe that was nearly annihilated now supplies a judge.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Forty sons and thirty grandsons riding on seventy donkeys — the highest-status marker among the minor judges (Jair had thirty sons on thirty donkeys, 10:4; Abdon has seventy mounts across two generations). Riding a donkey signals aristocratic status in the ancient Near East (Num 22, 1 Sam 25:20); the number of mounts signals the breadth of his household&rsquo;s honor.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Buried at Pirathon in Ephraim, in the Amalekite hill country — <em>bəhar hāʿămālêqî</em> notes that this region was once occupied by Amalek, a reminder that the land Israel inhabits came at a cost. The minor judge series closes here; Samson&rsquo;s annunciation follows immediately as the next era begins.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>The sin-cycle formula: <em>wayyôsipû bənê Yiśrāʾēl laʿăśôt hāraʿ bəʿênê YHWH</em> — &ldquo;the Israelites again did evil in the sight of the LORD.&rdquo; Forty years of Philistine oppression is the longest in Judges (cf. Midian 7 years, Ammon 18 years). The Philistines — sea-peoples settled on the Coastal Plain — represent a qualitatively different and more persistent threat than the Transjordanian enemies of earlier chapters.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>ʿăqārāh</em> (H6135, barren/sterile) — Manoah&rsquo;s wife joins the barren-matriarch sequence: Sarah (Gen 11:30), Rebekah (Gen 25:21), Rachel (Gen 29:31), Hannah (1 Sam 1:2), Elizabeth (Luke 1:7). Each barrenness is a narrative marker for divine intervention; the child born from barrenness carries a special commission. <em>wəhîʾ lōʾ yālādāh</em> (she had borne no children) confirms the condition, not merely a state of delay.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>malʾak YHWH</em> (H4397 + H3068, Angel of the LORD) — the definite article identifies this as the recurring divine messenger of the Exodus and pre-Sinai narratives (Gen 16, 22; Exod 3; Judg 2, 6). The angel&rsquo;s appearance to the woman first — before Manoah receives any word — is unusual; she receives the annunciation directly. <em>wəhinnāḵ hārāh</em> (and you shall conceive) uses the participial construction of immediate future, identical to Isa 7:14 LXX.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The dietary prohibitions are addressed to the mother as preparation: <em>haššāmərî nāʾ wəʾal-tištî yayin wəšēḵār</em> — &ldquo;be careful, drink no wine or strong drink.&rdquo; <em>šēḵār</em> (H7941, strong drink) is any fermented beverage other than wine. The Nazirite regulations will bind the child from the womb; the mother&rsquo;s observance during pregnancy extends the Nazirite restrictions to gestation.</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>nāzîr ʾĕlōhîm</em> (H5139, consecrated one of God) — Nazirite, from <em>nāzar</em> (to separate, consecrate). Unlike the voluntary Nazirite vow of Num 6 (which is temporary), Samson&rsquo;s consecration is lifelong and prenatal — imposed before birth. <em>hûʾ yāḥēl ləhôšîaʿ ʾet-Yiśrāʾēl</em> — &ldquo;he will begin to save Israel.&rdquo; <em>yāḥēl</em> (H2490, begin) signals incomplete deliverance; Samson&rsquo;s salvation is inaugural, not final. <em>hôšîaʿ</em> (H3467) is the verbal root of Joshua (<em>yəhôšûaʿ</em>) and Jesus (<em>Iēsous</em>).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The woman&rsquo;s report to Manoah: <em>ʾîš hāʾĕlōhîm</em> (man of God, H376 + H430) — the conventional prophetic title; she does not yet recognize him as an angel. <em>mōrāʾ məʾōd</em> (very awesome/terrifying) — she perceives the visitor&rsquo;s superhuman nature without identifying it. <em>wəlōʾ šəʾaltîhû ʾayyeh-miZZeh</em> — &ldquo;I did not ask him where he was from&rdquo; — the convention in theophany encounters is that the divine visitor&rsquo;s origin is not to be interrogated.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The woman rehearses the message: the angel&rsquo;s prohibition on wine and unclean food, the Nazirite status from birth. The repetition in vv.4-5 and 7 is a narrative device that emphasizes the requirements and confirms the woman&rsquo;s faithful transmission to her husband.</p>",
    "8": "<p><em>bî ʾădōnāy</em> — &ldquo;O Lord.&rdquo; Manoah&rsquo;s prayer addresses YHWH as <em>ʾădōnāy</em> (H136, the Lord) — the reverent substitute for the divine name. His request is pastoral rather than skeptical: <em>yəlammēdēnû mah-naʿăśeh lannnaʿar hayyûllād</em> — &ldquo;teach us what to do for the child who will be born.&rdquo; He wants instruction for raising the commissioned child, not proof of the message.</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>wayyišmaʿ hāʾĕlōhîm bəqôl Mānôaḥ</em> — &ldquo;God listened to the voice of Manoah.&rdquo; The Hiphil <em>šāmaʿ</em> here is divine attentiveness: prayer was heard and acted on. The angel returns, but again <em>ʾel-hāʾiššāh</em> (to the woman) — while she sits in the field, without Manoah present. The woman remains the primary recipient of the divine communication.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The woman acts with urgency (<em>wattəmaher</em>, she hurried) to bring Manoah. Her role is mediating — she receives and transmits the divine encounter to her husband. The narrative structure consistently gives her perceptive priority over Manoah, who will need guidance where she understood intuitively.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Manoah&rsquo;s question: <em>hattāh hāʾîš ʾăšer-dibbartā ʾel-hāʾiššāh</em> — &ldquo;Are you the man who spoke to this woman?&rdquo; He addresses the angel as a man — not wrong at this point, since the angel appears in human form. The angel&rsquo;s reply (<em>ʾănî</em>, I am) is laconic; he does not volunteer his identity.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>mišpaṭ hannaʿar</em> — &ldquo;the rule for the child.&rdquo; <em>mišpaṭ</em> (H4941, judgment/ordinance/custom) frames child-rearing as covenantally ordered; Manoah asks for the divinely appointed way of life for the consecrated child. This is a more theologically sophisticated question than simple curiosity.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The angel refers Manoah back to what the woman was already told — confirming the authority of her reception of the message. The doubling of instruction (vv.4-5 to the woman; v13 back to the woman) structurally underscores that she is the primary recipient.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Nazirite requirements restated comprehensively: nothing from the vine, no wine or strong drink, nothing unclean — all three Num 6 food restrictions applied to the mother during pregnancy. The totality of the prenatal Nazirite framework is emphasized; nothing of the sacred separation is to be compromised.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Manoah&rsquo;s hospitality: <em>nəʿaṣṣərāh nāʾ ʾôtāḵā</em> — &ldquo;let us detain you.&rdquo; The verb <em>ʿāṣar</em> (H6113, to detain/hold back) is the same used when Abraham urged the three visitors to stay (Gen 18:3-5). The offer of a kid for the meal recalls Abraham&rsquo;s hospitality; Manoah does not yet know he is hosting the divine.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The angel refuses the meal but redirects: <em>ʾim-taʿăśeh ʿôlāh laYHWH taʿălennāh</em> — &ldquo;if you offer a burnt offering, offer it to YHWH.&rdquo; This refusal distinguishes the angel from a human guest who would eat, and from a pagan deity who would require a ritual meal; the burnt offering to YHWH is the appropriate form of worship. <em>kî lōʾ yādaʿ Mānôaḥ</em> — the narrator explains: Manoah still does not know he is speaking to the Angel of the LORD.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Manoah asks the angel&rsquo;s name to know whom to honor when the promise is fulfilled: <em>ləḵabbdəḵā</em> — to honor you. The motive is appropriate (honoring one&rsquo;s benefactor) but the angel&rsquo;s response reveals that a name would be inadequate to contain his identity.</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>lāmmāh zeh tišʾal lišmî wəhûʾ-pelîʾî</em> — &ldquo;Why do you ask my name, seeing it is wonderful/beyond understanding?&rdquo; <em>pālîʾ</em> / <em>pelîʾî</em> (H6383) derives from <em>pālāʾ</em> (H6381, to be wonderful, to be beyond ordinary comprehension). The same root appears in the messianic title of Isa 9:6: <em>peleʾ yôʿēṣ</em> (Wonderful Counselor). The angel&rsquo;s name-refusal is itself a theophanic disclosure: his name is beyond human categories of understanding.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Manoah takes the kid and grain offering and offers them on the rock to YHWH — the rock as improvised altar recalls Gideon&rsquo;s theophany (6:20-21). <em>hammalpîʾ laʿăśôt</em> — &ldquo;the one who works wonders&rdquo; — the participial phrase identifies YHWH/the angel as the subject of miraculous action during the sacrifice. <em>wayyapleʾ</em> (and he worked wondrously) confirms the theophany.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The fire theophany: <em>baaʿălôt hallahav mēʿal hammizbaḥ</em> — &ldquo;as the flame went up from the altar.&rdquo; The angel of the LORD ascended in the flame — echoing Elijah&rsquo;s fire-descent from heaven (1 Kgs 18) and the pillar of fire in the Exodus. Manoah and his wife fell on their faces; prostration is the appropriate response to divine presence.</p>",
    "21": "<p><em>wəlōʾ-yāsap malʾak YHWH lĕhērāʾôt</em> — &ldquo;the Angel of the LORD did not appear again.&rdquo; The cessation of appearances functions as interpretive closure: the angel&rsquo;s work is complete. <em>ʾāz yādaʿ Mānôaḥ kî-malʾak YHWH hûʾ</em> — &ldquo;then Manoah realized that he had been the Angel of the LORD.&rdquo; The recognition arrives after the encounter ends, not during it — a recurring feature of theophany narratives (Gen 32:30; Luke 24:31).</p>",
    "22": "<p><em>mût nāmût</em> — emphatic (absolute infinitive + finite): &ldquo;we will certainly die.&rdquo; Manoah&rsquo;s fear is theologically grounded: the tradition that seeing God brings death (Exod 33:20; Judg 6:22). The phrase <em>ʾĕlōhîm rāʾînû</em> — &ldquo;we have seen God&rdquo; — confirms that the Angel of the LORD&rsquo;s identity equates with seeing YHWH himself; the narrative does not distinguish the angel from God.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The wife&rsquo;s response is a model of theological reasoning under fear: three parallel conditionals — if YHWH had wanted to kill us, he would not have (1) accepted the burnt offering, (2) shown us these things, (3) announced the coming child. Her logic moves from divine action to divine intention; what YHWH has already done is evidence of what he intends. The narrator gives the wife the final word in the theological debate between the two, a pattern of her superior perception throughout ch13.</p>",
    "24": "<p><em>watteqrāʾ ʾet-šəmô Šimšôn</em> — &ldquo;she named him Samson.&rdquo; It is the mother who names the child — she received the annunciation, and she claims the naming. <em>Šimšôn</em> may derive from <em>šemeš</em> (H8121, sun), appropriate for a Danite hero from the Sorek valley near Bethshemesh (house of the sun). <em>wayyiḡdal hannaʿar wayyəḇāreḵēhû YHWH</em> — the divine blessing at birth is the same formula used for Samson as for Samuel (1 Sam 3:19) and John the Baptist (Luke 1:80).</p>",
    "25": "<p><em>wattāḥel rûaḥ YHWH lipʿămô</em> — &ldquo;the Spirit of the LORD began to stir him.&rdquo; <em>pāʿam</em> (H6470, to beat/push/stir) describes the intermittent, recurrent movement of the Spirit; it is not a continuous indwelling but a periodic stirring — different from the Spirit coming upon a judge for a single event. <em>bəmaḥănēh-dān</em> (in the camp of Dan) between Zorah and Eshtaol — the encampment where the Spirit begins to move becomes the geographic theater for Samson&rsquo;s coming exploits.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-original', 'judges')
    merge_comm(existing, JUDGES)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'judges', existing)
    print('Judges 11-13 mkt-original written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
